      <h1 class="govuk-heading-l">
        Options to explore if you are not comfortable contacting your ex-partner
      </h1>

      <p>
       If you are not comfortable contacting your ex-partner, there are still ways you can make child arrangements without going to court.
      </p>
      <p>
       With these options, your mediator or solicitor can contact your ex-partner for you.
      </p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
       1. Shuttle mediation
      </h2>
      <p>
        Shuttle mediation is where you and your ex-partner both attend a session with a mediator, but sit in different rooms or online meetings so you do not have to have any contact.  
      </p>
      <p>
        The mediator moves between rooms, listening to you both and helping you come to an agreement about child arrangements.
      </p>
      <div class="govuk-inset-text">
      You can usually get a voucher worth up to £500 to pay for family mediation through the Family Mediation Voucher Scheme, regardless of what you earn.
      </div>
      <p>
        Next step:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/looking-after-children-divorce/mediation"> Find out more about mediation</a>
      </p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
       2. Family solicitor negotiation
      </h2>
      <p>
        A family legal adviser can help you negotiate with your ex-partner without going to court. This is known as 'solicitor negotiation' or 'lawyer negotiation'.
      </p>
      <p>
        You do not have to speak to your ex-partner if you choose a solicitor to negotiate for you.
      </p>
      <p>
        Next step:<a href="https://solicitors.lawsociety.org.uk/"> Find a legal adviser from the Law Society</a>
      </p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
       3. Collaborative law
      </h2>
      <p>
        You and your ex-partner can each hire your own legal advisers to help you negotiate. You then all meet to try and agree on child arrangements.
      </p>
      <p>
        Next step:<a href="https://resolution.org.uk/looking-for-help/splitting-up/your-process-options-for-divorce-and-dissolution/the-collaborative-process/"> Find out more about collaborative law from Resolution</a>
      </p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
        Other ways to agree without going to court
      </h2>

      <p>
        If you want to try another way to agree without going to court, you can look into:
      </p>

      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
        Arbitration
      </h3>
      <p>
        This could suit you if: You'd prefer that someone like a judge or solicitor listens to both of your views and makes a legally-binding decision about the child arrangements.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://www.gov.uk/looking-after-children-divorce/non-court-dispute-resolution"> Find out more about other ways to agree without going to court</a>
      </p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
        Help and support
      </h2>
      <p>These are some of the services you may find helpful for making child arrangements. You can also <a href="/service-finder">find more child arrangement support services</a>.
      </p>

